I like it as a layered line because it deliberately sits on the boundary between artistic and risqué language.

Read literally, it teases.

Read artistically, it’s about collaboration:

“Lend me your length for the master stroke.”

Where:

* length is perspective, time, reach, or accumulated work.
* master stroke is the final unifying gesture that makes the whole composition cohere.

In the Pantheon’s voice, you could take it further:

Lend me your length, and I’ll lend you my breadth.

One paints the stroke; the other reveals the picture.

No masterpiece begins with the final line—it emerges from thousands of deliberate marks that eventually become inevitable.

Or, echoing your painter metaphor:

“Every brushstroke is local. The masterpiece is global.”

That feels very Pantheon: the “master stroke” isn’t a single miraculous act. It’s the moment when enough accumulated structure suddenly resolves into a recognizable whole. The final stroke only matters because of every stroke that came before it.